member.summary: Data about Dividends provided by the Company

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundamentals.DividendInformation.LastDividendExDate
member.summary: The major exchanges require 4 business days prior to the Record Date for recording ownership changes. The day that begins this 4-day period is the Ex-Date. Investors who purchase the stock prior to the Ex-Date are eligible for the latest dividend; investors who purchase the stock on or after the Ex-Date are not entitled to the dividend. Empirical evidence has shown that this is also the date that the market reflects the dividend policy in the stock price.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundamentals.DividendInformation.DividendRate
member.summary: If a company's board has committed to dividend payments in the future, the latest reported dividend rate equals the number of times the company pays dividends per year times the latest dividend, expressed in dollars. If a company's board has not committed to dividend payments in the future, the latest reported dividend rate equals the total dividends paid in the past 12 months.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundamentals.DividendInformation.LastDividendYield
member.summary: is the latest dividend rate divided by the latest closing price.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundamentals.DividendInformation.PayoutRatio
member.summary: The current payout is the LTM dividend per share divided by LTM EPS, expressed as a percentage. The percentage indicates the percent of EPS that was paid out as a dividend.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundamentals.DividendInformation.PayoutFiveYearAverageFromTotalOperations
member.summary: 5-Year average payout is the sum of the actual dividends paid per share as reported in the annual report divided by the total diluted EPS from the annual report divided by 5.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundamentals.DividendInformation.PayoutFromTotalOperationsLatestFiscalYear
member.summary: The latest fiscal year payout is the fiscal dividend per share divided by the fiscal EPS, expressed as a percentage. The percentage indicates the percent of EPS that was paid out as a dividend.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundamentals.DividendInformation.DividendYieldFiveYearAverage
member.summary: 5-Year average dividend yield is the sum of the actual dividend yield calculations from the past five fiscal years divided by 5.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundamentals.LatestClosePriceChangeStatistics.PriceMomentumThisWeek
member.summary: Measures the annualized rate at which the stock is changing in price. The index is constructed as follows: First, four moving averages are calculated, based on daily closing prices: a 30-week, a 10-week, a 10-day and a 5-day average. The 5-day and 10-day averages are then combined and divided by 2, to represent the current price level. From that point, equations are applied to the averages to measure the changes in the price level. The result i then compounded to represent the approximate annual rate of change.

member.summary: The date of the fund's Annual Report.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundFundamentals.AnnualReportSummary.NetIncomeRatio
member.summary: This ratio reveals the percentage of current income earned per share.

member.summary: The Gross Expense Ratio represents the total gross expenses (net expenses with waivers added back in) divided by the fund's average net assets

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundFundamentals.AnnualReportSummary.AnnualReportNetExpenseRatio
member.summary: The percentage of fund assets used to pay for operating expenses and management fees, including 12b-1 fees, administrative fees, and all other asset-based costs incurred by the fund, except brokerage costs.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundFundamentals.AnnualReportSummary.AverageNetAssets
member.summary: This is a 12-month trailing average as of the Annual Report's date

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundFundamentals.AnnualReportSummary.AverageNetAssetsNumberOfMonthCovered
member.summary: The number of months used to calculate average net assets

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundFundamentals.AnnualReportSummary.GrossIncome
member.summary: It is a percentage based on the total amount of income generated by the investment portfolio.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundFundamentals.AnnualReportSummary.UnrealizedCapitalGain
member.summary: A capital gain is the difference between an asset's selling price and the purchase price, or the amount by which the asset's purchase price has appreciated

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundFundamentals.AnnualReportSummary.RealizedCapitalGain
member.summary: A capital gain is the difference between an asset's selling price and purchase price, or the amount by which the asset's purchase price has appreciated.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundFundamentals.AnnualReportSummary.TurnoverRatio
member.summary: A measure of the portfolio manager's trading activity which is computed by taking the lesser of purchases or sales (excluding all securities with maturities of less than one year) and dividing by average monthly net assets

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFundFundamentals.AnnualReportSummary.TurnoverRatioDate
member.summary: The date when the turnover ratio was reported.

member.summary: This indicates if the fund distributes daily dividends. Daily dividends are small dividends that are declared on a daily basis. These daily dividends accumulate over time (since a new dividend is declared daily), and are eventually paid on a monthly or quarterly basis.

member.summary: The number of times per year that a fund intends to make payments from dividends.

member.summary: Number of times per year that a fund intends to make payments from Capital Gains. Generally monthly, quarterly, semiannually, or annually. The Distribution schedule can be denoted as one of the following: Annually, Monthly,Quarterly,Semi-Annually,Varies,Daily,None,Weekly,Bimonthly,Biweekly,Semimonthly.

summary.p: The precision unit to apply to the ticks of the chart. Choose:

ul.li: Tick to draw one point per trade (could be thousands for highly traded securities). TickPeriods does not apply in this case.
Milliseconds to summarize trades by the number of milliseconds specified by TickPeriods.
Second to summarize trades by the number of seconds specified by TickPeriods.
Minute to summarize trades by the number of minutes specified by TickPeriods.

summary.p: For instance TickPeriod=2 and TickPrecision=Minute will plot one value of the chart for trades executed every two minutes.

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteFunds.GetLatestNAV(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFunds.IdentifierTypes)
member.summary: Returns the latest closing NAV for a fund.
member.param: The identifier for the fund as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. Examples: FMAGX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key for the companies, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
Use the LookupCIK operation to find the CIK for a company.
CUSIP: Identifier is the CUSIP for the companies.
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the symbol for the company, e.g. MSFT, DELL, or ORCL.
Supports multiple symbologies, check here for details.
ISIN: Identifier is the ISIN 12-character alpha numeric code identifying a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteFutures.GetTicks(System.String,System.Int32,System.Int32,System.String,System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFutures.TickPeriod,System.Int32)
member.summary: Returns a set of tick-by-tick quotes for a future and a time range during the trading day.You can choose to return every tick (trade) for this time range by choosing Tick as the TickPrecision. Or you can choose to summarize ticks by a certain number of milliseconds, seconds, or minutes.Warning: Since most securities are traded multiple times per second, the returned data set of a multi-hour tick-by-tick range can be large.
member.param: The symbol for the future contract. Examples: CL
The contract month for the future contract. Use 0 for month and 0 for year for front future. Use 0 for month and current year for spot prices. Examples: 1
The contract year for the future contract. Use 0 for month and 0 for year for front future. Use 0 for month and current year for spot prices. Examples: 2016

The start time (EST) for the range (use the HH:MM:SS.mmmm) format. For instance, you would enter 3:00 PM EST as 15:00:00.0000. you can omit seconds and milliseconds. The earliest available time is 7:00:00. Examples: 8:00

The start time (EST) for the range (use the HH:MM:SS.mmmm) format. For instance, you would enter 12:00 PM EST as 12:00:00.0000. you can omit seconds and milliseconds. The latest available time is 20:00:00. Examples: 20:00

The precision unit to apply to the ticks of the return array. Choose:
Tick to draw one point per trade (could be slow for highly traded securities). TickPeriods will not apply.
Milliseconds to summarize trades by the number of milliseconds specified by TickPeriods.
Second to summarize trades by the number of seconds specified by TickPeriods.
Minute to summarize trades by the number of minutes specified by TickPeriods. Examples: Tick

Used in combination with TickPrecision to define the number of points displayed on the chart. For instance TickPeriods=5 with TickPrecision=Minute will display one data point every 5 minutes with the point being the average price for that period. Examples: 1

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteFutures.GetHistoricalTicksAsOfDate(System.String,System.Int32,System.Int32,System.String,System.String,System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteFutures.TickPeriod,System.Int32)
member.summary: Returns a set of tick-by-tick quotes for a historical time range on AsOfDate.You can choose to return every tick (trade) for this time range by choosing Tick as the TickPrecision. Or you can choose to summarize ticks by a certain number of milliseconds, seconds, or minutes.Warning: Since most securities are traded multiple times per second, the returned data set of a multi-hour tick-by-tick range can be large.
member.param: The symbol for the future. Examples: CL
The delivery month for the future contract. Use 0 for spot prices. Examples: 1
The contract year for the future contract. Use the current year for spot prices. Examples: 2015
The trading date for the historical future ticks. Historical future ticks are kept on line for 30 days. Examples: 8/22/2014

The start time (EST) for the range (use the HH:MM:SS.mmmm) format. For instance, you would enter 3:00 PM EST as 15:00:00.0000. you can omit seconds and milliseconds. The earliest available time is 7:00:00. Examples: 8:00

The start time (EST) for the range (use the HH:MM:SS.mmmm) format. For instance, you would enter 12:00 PM EST as 12:00:00.0000. you can omit seconds and milliseconds. The latest available time is 20:00:00. Examples: 10:00

The precision unit to apply to the ticks of the return array. Choose:
Tick to draw one point per trade (could be slow for highly traded securities). TickPeriods will not apply.
Milliseconds to summarize trades by the number of milliseconds specified by TickPeriods.
Second to summarize trades by the number of seconds specified by TickPeriods.
Minute to summarize trades by the number of minutes specified by TickPeriods. Examples: Minute

Used in combination with TickPrecision to define the number of points displayed on the chart. For instance TickPeriods=5 with TickPrecision=Minute will display one data point every 5 minutes with the point being the average price for that period. Examples: 1

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalFundamentals.GetFundamental(Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalFundamentals.GlobalFundamentalTypes,System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalFundamentals.IdentifierTypes)
member.summary: Returns specific global fundamental values for a security.
member.param: The type of fundamental you are looking for. Examples: MarketCapitalization
The identifier for the global company or security as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. Examples: ULVR.L

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key for the companies, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
Use the LookupCIK operation to find the CIK for a company.
CUSIP: Identifier is the CUSIP for the companies.
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the symbol for the company, e.g. MSFT, DELL, or ORCL.
Supports multiple symbologies, check here for details.
ISIN: Identifier is the ISIN 12-character alpha numeric code identifying a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalHistorical.GetGlobalLastClosingPrice(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalHistorical.IdentifierTypes,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalHistorical.AdjustmentMethods)
member.summary: Returns the last global closing price for a specified security.
member.param: The identifier for the company as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. Examples: BMW.XETR

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the SEC Central Index Key for the company.
Use the LookupCIK operation to find the CIK for a company.
CUSIP: Identifier is the CUSIP for the company.
CUSIPS are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the symbol for the global company, e.g. BMW.XETR.
Supports multiple Symbologies, check here for details.
ISIN: Identifier is the ISIN 12-character alpha numeric code identifying a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a Swiss financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

Method for adjusting prices. Adjusted price output fields have "Adjusted" in their field names. Note that US Historical quotes retrieved using this method will always be split-adjusted only. Valid Values are:
None: No adjustment made.
SplitOnly: Adjustments made for splits, but not dividends.
CashDividendOnly: Cash (not stock) dividends adjusted.
SplitAndCashDividend: Both splits and cash dividends adjusted.
SplitAndProportionalCashDividend: Both splits and cash dividends adjusted, but dividend adjustments use the percentage of the dividend vs. the price.
All: Same as SplitAndCashDividend.
DefaultValue: Same as SplitAndCashDividend. Examples: SplitOnly

member.summary: Returns historical end of day price for list of securities.
member.param: Instrument identifier for which end of day quote is needed Examples: BMW.XETR

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the SEC Central Index Key for the company.
Use the LookupCIK operation to find the CIK for a company.
CUSIP: Identifier is the CUSIP for the company.
CUSIPS are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the symbol for the global company, e.g. BMW.XETR.
Supports multiple Symbologies, check here for details.
ISIN: Identifier is the ISIN 12-character alpha numeric code identifying a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a Swiss financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

Method for adjusting prices. Adjusted price output fields have "Adjusted" in their field names. Note that US Historical quotes retrieved using this method will always be split-adjusted only. Valid Values are:
None: No adjustment made.
SplitOnly: Adjustments made for splits, but not dividends.
CashDividendOnly: Cash (not stock) dividends adjusted.
SplitAndCashDividend: Both splits and cash dividends adjusted.
SplitAndProportionalCashDividend: Both splits and cash dividends adjusted, but dividend adjustments use the percentage of the dividend vs. the price.
All: Same as SplitAndCashDividend.
DefaultValue: Same as SplitAndCashDividend. Examples: SplitOnly

Method to be used to determine end of day price. Supported values are: LastTrade: Always returns the price of last known trade price as end of day price. On zero volume days, return the last known trade price for the most recent day on which the security traded. Valuation: This returns Valuation price based on the rules specified by the exchange. ExchangeLastTrade: This return the Closing price, if available from exchange, or Last traded price. Note: All exchange may not provide closing price. ExchangeValuation: This method returns Closing price, if available, or Valuation price. Examples: LastTrade
The date for which quote data is required, specified in MM/DD/YYYY format. Examples: 03/20/2012

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalHistorical.GetSplitRatio(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalHistorical.IdentifierTypes,System.String,System.String)
member.summary: Return the cumulative split ratio for a security between two dates.For instance, if a security saw a 3:1 split and 2:1 split during the period, the split ratio 6 is returned. Returns 1 if no split occurred.
member.param: The identifier for the company as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. For non-U.S. securities, the market code must be appended to the Identifier. For example, BMW.XETR, BMW.XETR, DE0005190003.DE or DE0005190003.XETR. Examples: BMW.XETR

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the SEC Central Index Key for the company.
Use the LookupCIK operation to find the CIK for a company.
CUSIP: Identifier is the CUSIP for the company.
CUSIPS are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the symbol for the global company, e.g. BMW.XETR.
Supports multiple Symbologies, check here for details.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a Swiss financial instrument.
ISIN: Identifier is the ISIN 12-character alpha numeric code identifying a security. Examples: Symbol
The start date for the range. Examples: 8/24/2013
The end date for the range. Examples: 8/22/2014

member.summary: The time for the Last index price.

summary.p: The the offset or difference, in hours, from the local exchange time to UTC. For example, the offset is -5 for Eastern Standard Time. This offset value is applicable to the Last price time (the Time output parameter) returned.
This property can be used to convert the Time to UTC:

ul.li: Formula: Time - UTCOffset = UTC
Example: Time=3:00 PM and UTCOffset=-5 results in UTC=8:00 PM.

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalIndicesHistorical.GetLastClosingIndexValue(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalIndicesHistorical.IdentifierTypes)
member.summary: Returns the last closing value for an index.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the index as determined by the IdentifierType parameter.You must access indices using index groups (see note). Note: an index group suffix MUST be appended to all index identifiers. In this example INDCBSX is the index group appended to the index symbol SPX. For a list of index groups and indices available on each, use ListIndexGroups and ListIndicesByIndexGroup, respectively. Examples: SPX.INDCBSX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the ticker symbol for the security, e.g. SPX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

summary.p: The the offset or difference, in hours, from the local exchange time to UTC. For example, the offset is -5 for Eastern Standard Time. This offset value is applicable to the Last price time (the Time output parameter) returned.

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalIndicesRealTime.GetRealTimeIndexValue(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalIndicesRealTime.IdentifierTypes)
member.summary: Returns the real-time value for an index.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the index as determined by the IdentifierType parameter.You must access indices using index groups (see note). Note: an index group suffix MUST be appended to all index identifiers. In this example INDCBSX is the index group appended to the index symbol SPX. For a list of index groups and indices available on each, use ListIndexGroups and ListIndicesByIndexGroup, respectively. Examples: SPX.INDCBSX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the ticker symbol for the security, e.g. SPX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalIndicesRealTime.GetIndexBar(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalIndicesRealTime.IdentifierTypes,System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalIndicesRealTime.BarPrecision,System.Int32)
member.summary: Returns a single real time summarized index data bar for a specific time during the trading day.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the index as determined by the IdentifierType parameter.You must access indices using index groups (see note). Note: an index group suffix MUST be appended to all index identifiers. In this example INDCBSX is the index group appended to the index symbol SPX. For a list of index groups and indices available on each, use ListIndexGroups and ListIndicesByIndexGroup, respectively. Examples: SPX.INDCBSX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the ticker symbol for the security, e.g. SPX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The ending time for the set of index bars (in the local index provider's time zone).
Note that the system's schedule runs on UTC time so to retrieve data without ambiguity, please using the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the index. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 9:30 AM

The precision unit to apply to the index bars. Choose:
Minutes to summarize index quotes by the number of minutes specified by Periods.
Hours to summarize index quotes by the number of hours specified by Periods.
For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=30 will return one index bar every thirty minutes, including the open, high, low and close within that thirty minute period. Examples: Minute
Used in combination with Precision to define the number of units to apply to index bars. For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=30 will return one index bar every thirty minutes. Examples: 1

summary.p: The the offset or difference, in hours, from the local exchange time to UTC. For example, the offset is -5 for Eastern Standard Time. This offset value is applicable to the Last price time (the Time output parameter) returned.
This property can be used to convert the Time to UTC:

ul.li: Formula: Time - UTCOffset = UTC
Example: Time=3:00 PM and UTCOffset=-5 results in UTC=8:00 PM.

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalIndices.GetDelayedIndexValue(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalIndices.IdentifierTypes)
member.summary: Returns the delayed value for an index.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the index as determined by the IdentifierType parameter.You must access indices using index groups (see note). Note: an index group suffix MUST be appended to all index identifiers. In this example INDCBSX is the index group appended to the index symbol SPX. For a list of index groups and indices available on each, use ListIndexGroups and ListIndicesByIndexGroup, respectively. Examples: SPX.INDCBSX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the ticker symbol for the security, e.g. SPX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalIndices.GetIndexBar(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalIndices.IdentifierTypes,System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalIndices.BarPrecision,System.Int32)
member.summary: Returns a single delayed summarized index data bar for a specific time during the trading day.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the index as determined by the IdentifierType parameter.You must access indices using index groups (see note). Note: an index group suffix MUST be appended to all index identifiers. In this example INDCBSX is the index group appended to the index symbol SPX. For a list of index groups and indices available on each, use ListIndexGroups and ListIndicesByIndexGroup, respectively. Examples: SPX.INDCBSX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the ticker symbol for the security, e.g. SPX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The ending time for the set of index bars (in the local index provider's time zone).
Note that the system's schedule runs on UTC time so to retrieve data without ambiguity, please use the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the index. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 9:30 AM

The precision unit to apply to the index bars. Choose:
Minutes to summarize index quotes by the number of minutes specified by Periods.
Hours to summarize index quotes by the number of hours specified by Periods.
For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=30 will return one index bar every thirty minutes, including the open, high, low and close within that thirty minute period. Examples: Minute
Used in combination with Precision to define the number of units to apply to index bars. For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=30 will return one index bar every thirty minutes. Examples: 1

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalMaster.ListIdentifiersByExchange(Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalMaster.Exchanges,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalMaster.IdentifierTypes,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalMaster.InstrumentClasses,System.String)
member.summary: Lists identifiers of a specified type for a given exchange.
member.param:
The Market Identification Code (MIC) for the exchange.
To view a list of the supported exchanges use the ListExchanges operation. Examples: XNAS

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. NESN.VX.
This field supports multiple symbologies (e.g. NESN.VX or NESN.XVTX).
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha-numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The instrument type. Valid values are:
All
Bond
Commodity
Currency
CurrencyForward
DepositoryReceipt
Derivative
ExchangeTradedFund
Fund
Indices
InterestRateSwaps
MoneyMarket
Other
Stock
StructuredProduct
Technical Examples: Stock
The date for which to return active records. Examples: 8/22/2014

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalNews.Security.CIK
member.summary: The Central Index Key (CIK) for this security. This is a number given to an individual or company by the United States Securities and Exchange Commission. The number is used to identify the filings of a company, person, or entity in several online databases, including EDGAR.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalNews.Security.CUSIP
member.summary: The CUSIP for this security. The CUSIP is a 9-character alphanumeric code which identifies a North American financial security for the purposes of facilitating clearing and settlement of trades. Note that use of this identifier requires a license from S&P Capital IQ. If you are not entitled to to receive CUSIP identifiers, then this field will be empty.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalNews.Security.Symbol
member.summary: The symbol for this security.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalNews.Security.ISIN
member.summary: The ISIN for this security. The ISIN code is a 12-character alpha-numerical code that does not contain information characterizing financial instruments but serves for uniform identification of a security at trading and settlement. Similar to the CUSIP, use of this identifier for US-based securities require a license from S&P Capital IQ. Use of this identifier for non-US securities does not carry this restriction. Thus if you are requested a US-based security and are not entitled to receive ISIN identifiers then this field will be empty.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalNews.Security.Valoren
member.summary: The Valoren (or VALOR number) is a code which uniquely identifies listed securities and financial instruments used in Switzerland, and serve a similar purpose to CUSIP or WKN in the North American or German markets respectively. Valorens are issued by SIX Financial Information.

member.param: The identifier for the company as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. Examples: MSFT

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the SEC Central Index Key for the company.
Use the LookupCIK operation to find the CIK for a company.
CUSIP: Identifier is the CUSIP for the company.

Symbol: Identifier is the symbol for the company, e.g. MSFT, DELL, or ORCL.
Supports multiple Symbologies, check here for details.
ISIN: Identifier is the ISIN 12-character alpha numeric code identifying a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a Swiss financial instrument. Examples: Symbol
The number of headlines to return. Examples: 10

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalOptions.GetAllEquityOptionChain(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalOptions.IdentifierTypes,System.String,System.String)
member.summary: Returns the complete option chain for an equity.
member.param: The identifier for the company or security as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. Examples: MSFT

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. MSFT.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The identifier type for the option contract(s). Leave blank for OSISymbol.
Valid values are:
OSISymbol: The 21-character identifier for the option as determined by the Option Symbology Initiative (OSI) symbology key.
DTNSymbol: The 7- to 17-character identifier for the option as determined by the Telvent DTN (DTN) symbology key.
ListingSymbol: The symbol used by the exchange where the security is listed. For OPRA, ListingSymbol can be up to 17 characters, (e.g. MSFTD20134290000). OSISymbol and DTNSymbol are only supported for OPRA options. For Montreal Exchange and Euronext Liffe only ListingSymbol is supported.
If SymbologyType is blank, the API will parse the Symbol provided. The results could be inaccurate if the symbol is ambiguous (e.g. it could be a valid DTNSymbol and a valid ListingSymbol, but not for the same otpion). Please specify SymbologyType if possible. Examples:

The market where the option is listed or quoted. Leave blank for OPRA.
Valid values are:
_OPRA (OPRA)
XMOD (Montreal)
XLIF (EuronextLiffe) Examples:

member.summary: Calculates the value of an option using the Black-Scholes model.
member.param: The option type. Valid values are Call and Put. Examples: Call
The current price of the underlying security. Examples: 28
The strike price of the option. Examples: 35
The number of years until the option expiration date. Examples: 0.5

The volatility of the underlying security. For example, enter 0.25 for 25%. Examples: 0.25

summary.p: The offset or difference, in hours, from the local exchange time to UTC. For example, the offset is -5 for Eastern Standard Time. This offset value is applicable to the Last price time (the Time output parameter) returned.
This property can be used to convert the Time to UTC:

ul.li: Formula: Time - UTCOffset = UTC
Example: Time=3:00 PM and UTCOffset=-5 results in UTC=8:00 PM.

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalQuotes.GetGlobalDelayedQuote(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalQuotes.IdentifierTypes)
member.summary: Returns a delayed quote for a global security.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the security as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. You must access quotes using an exchange suffix (see note). Note: an exchange suffix MUST be appended to all global security identifiers. In this example XVTX is the exchange suffix (market identification code) appended to the global security symbol NESN. For a list of exchange market identification codes use ListExchanges. Examples: NESN.XVTX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. NESN.XVTX.
This field supports multiple symbologies (e.g. NESN.XVTX or NESN.VX).
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha-numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

member.param: A comma-delimited list of fully qualified identifiers for securities as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. You must access quotes using an exchange suffix (see note). Note: an exchange suffix MUST be appended to all global security identifiers. In this example XVTX is the exchange suffix (market identification code) appended to the global security symbol NESN. For a list of exchange market identification codes use ListExchanges. Examples: NESN.XVTX,BMW.XETR

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. NESN.XVTX.
This field supports multiple symbologies (e.g. NESN.XVTX or NESN.VX).
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha-numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalQuotes.GetGlobalIntradayVWAP(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalQuotes.IdentifierTypes,System.String,System.String)
member.summary: Returns a Volume-Weighted Average Price (VWAP) for a global security for a specified time period within the day.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the security as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. You must access quotes using an exchange suffix (see note). Note: an exchange suffix MUST be appended to all global security identifiers. In this example CHIX is the exchange suffix (market identification code) appended to the global security symbol HSBA1. For a list of exchange market identification codes use ListExchanges. Examples: HSBAl.CHIX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. HSBAl.CHIX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha-numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The starting time for the Intraday VWAP (in the exchange's local time zone).
Please use the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the exchange. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 9:30 AM

The ending time for the Intraday VWAP (in the exchange's local time zone).
Please use the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the exchange. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 10:00 AM

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalQuotes.GetBar(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalQuotes.IdentifierTypes,System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalQuotes.TickPrecisions,System.Int32)
member.summary: Returns a single summarized quote bar for a specific time during the trading day.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the security as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. You must access quotes using an exchange suffix (see note). Note: an exchange suffix MUST be appended to all global security identifiers. In this example XVTX is the exchange suffix (market identification code) appended to the global security symbol NESN. For a list of exchange market identification codes use ListExchanges. Examples: NESN.XVTX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. NESN.XVTX.
This field supports multiple symbologies (e.g. NESN.XVTX or NESN.VX).
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha-numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The ending time for the summarized trade bar (in the exchange's local time zone).
Note that the system's schedule runs on UTC time so to retrieve data without ambiguity, please use the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the exchange. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 10:00 AM

The precision unit to apply to the summarized quote bars. Choose:
Seconds to summarize quotes by the number of seconds specified by Periods.
Minutes to summarize quotes by the number of minutes specified by Periods.
Hours to summarize quotes by the number of hours specified by Periods.
For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=15 will return one quote bar every fifteen minutes, including the open, high, low and close within that fifteen minute period. Examples: Minutes

Used in combination with Precision to define the number of units to apply to summarized quote bars. For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=15 will return one summarized quote bar every fifteen minutes. Examples: 15

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalQuotes.GetTopMarketMovers(Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalQuotes.MarketMoverTypes,System.Int32,System.String)
member.summary: Returns financial quotes about the top gaining, losing, or moving equities on an exchange.
member.param:
The type of market movers list. Choose:
PercentGainers to return the issues that have made the biggest gains by percent change in price from the previous close.
PercentLosers to return the issues that have made the biggest losses by percent change in price from the previous close.
MostActive to return the most active issues by volume for the current trading day Examples: PercentGainers

The number of market movers to return. The maximum number that may be requested is 50.
For example, TopType=PercentGainers and NumberOfTops=5 returns the top 5 percent gainers. Examples: 5

The market identification code of the listing exchange for which to return a market movers list. This parameter also accepts multiple values entered as a comma-delimited list. Use ListExchanges for a list of valid exchanges.
You must be entitled to the exchange(s) for which you are requesting data. Examples: XNYS,ARCX

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalRealTimeOptions.GetAllEquityOptionChain(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalRealTimeOptions.IdentifierTypes,System.String,System.String)
member.summary: Returns the complete option chain for an equity.
member.param: The identifier for the company or security as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. Examples: MSFT

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. MSFT.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The identifier type for the option contract(s).
Leave blank for OSISymbol. Valid values are:
OSISymbol: The 21-character identifier for the option as determined by the Option Symbology Initiative (OSI) symbology key.
DTNSymbol: The 7- to 17-character identifier for the option as determined by the Telvent DTN (DTN) symbology key. Examples:

The market where the option is listed or quoted.
Leave blank for _OPRA (OPRA). Examples:

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalRealTime.GetGlobalRealTimeQuote(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalRealTime.IdentifierTypes)
member.summary: Returns a real-time quote for a global security.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the security as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. You must access quotes using an exchange suffix (see note). Note: an exchange suffix MUST be appended to all global security identifiers. In this example CHIX is the exchange suffix (market identification code) appended to the global security symbol HSBA1. For a list of exchange market identification codes use ListExchanges. Examples: HSBAl.CHIX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. HSBAl.CHIX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha-numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

member.summary: Returns a Volume-Weighted Average Price (VWAP) for a global security for a specified time period within the day.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the security as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. You must access quotes using an exchange suffix (see note). For a list of exchange market identification codes use ListExchanges. Examples: HSBAl.CHIX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. HSBAl.CHIX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha-numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The starting time for the Intraday VWAP (in the exchange's local time zone).
Please use the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the exchange. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 9:30 AM

The ending time for the Intraday VWAP (in the exchange's local time zone).
Please use the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the exchange. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 10:00 AM

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteGlobalRealTime.GetBar(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalRealTime.IdentifierTypes,System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteGlobalRealTime.TickPrecisions,System.Int32)
member.summary: Returns a single summarized quote bar for a specific time during the trading day.
member.param: The fully qualified identifier for the security as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. You must access quotes using an exchange suffix (see note). Note: an exchange suffix MUST be appended to all global security identifiers. In this example CHIX is the exchange suffix (market identification code) appended to the global security symbol HSBA1. For a list of exchange market identification codes use ListExchanges. Examples: HSBAl.CHIX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. HSBAl.CHIX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha-numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The ending time for the summarized trade bar (in the exchange's local time zone).
Note that the system's schedule runs on UTC time so to retrieve data without ambiguity, please use the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the exchange. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 10:00 AM

The precision unit to apply to the summarized quote bars. Choose:
Seconds to summarize quotes by the number of seconds specified by Periods.
Minutes to summarize quotes by the number of minutes specified by Periods.
Hours to summarize quotes by the number of hours specified by Periods.
For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=15 will return one quote bar every fifteen minutes, including the open, high, low and close within that fifteen minute period. Examples: Minutes

Used in combination with Precision to define the number of units to apply to summarized quote bars. For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=15 will return one summarized quote bar every fifteen minutes. Examples: 15

Note: an exchange suffix MUST be appended to all global security identifiers. In this example CHIX is the exchange suffix (market identification code) appended to the global security symbol HSBA1. For a list of exchange market identification codes use ListExchanges. Examples: HSBAl.CHIX

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the Central Index Key assigned to a security's issuing company, which is a number used on SEC systems to identify companies and other registered entities.
CUSIP: Identifier is the number identifying all stock and registered bonds, using the Committee on Uniform Securities Identification Procedures (CUSIP).
CUSIPs are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the trading symbol for the security, e.g. HSBAl.CHIX.
ISIN: Identifier is the 12-character alpha-numeric International Securities Identification Number (ISO 6166 ISIN) assigned to a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

The starting time for the set of summarized trade bars (in the exchange's local time zone).
Note that the system's schedule runs on UTC time so to retrieve data without ambiguity, please use the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the exchange. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 9:30 AM

The ending time for the set of summarized trade bars (in the exchange's local time zone).
Note that the system's schedule runs on UTC time so to retrieve data without ambiguity, please use the following format: {date} {time}, where the date and time correspond to the local time of the exchange. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 8/24/2014 10:00 AM

The precision unit to apply to the summarized quote bars. Choose:
Seconds to summarize quotes by the number of seconds specified by Periods.
Minutes to summarize quotes by the number of minutes specified by Periods.
Hours to summarize quotes by the number of hours specified by Periods.
For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=15 will return one quote bar every fifteen minutes, including the open, high, low and close within that fifteen minute period. Examples: Minutes

Used in combination with Precision to define the number of units to apply to summarized quote bars. For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=15 will return one summarized quote bar every fifteen minutes. Examples: 15

member.summary: Returns financial quotes about the top gaining, losing, or moving equities on an exchange.
member.param:
The type of market movers list. Choose:
PercentGainers to return the issues that have made the biggest gains by percent change in price from the previous close.
PercentLosers to return the issues that have made the biggest losses by percent change in price from the previous close.
MostActive to return the most active issues by volume for the current trading day Examples: PercentGainers

The number of market movers to return. The maximum number that may be requested is 50.
For example, TopType=PercentGainers and NumberOfTops=5 returns the top 5 percent gainers. Examples: 5

The market identification code of the listing exchange for which to return a market movers list. This parameter also accepts multiple values entered as a comma-delimited list. Use ListExchanges for a list of valid exchanges.
You must be entitled to the exchange(s) for which you are requesting data. Examples: XNYS,ARCX

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteInsider.GetFilingAsText(System.String,System.Boolean)
member.summary: Retrieve a complete SEC ownership document (Form Types 3, 4 or 5) as Text. This operation returns the complete Header information for the file. The Content is also provided in the Content element. This content is slightly enriched over the raw content of the file: it can be displayed in an HTML document. Note that you can retrieve this file directly by using the TextFileUrl value. Use the FileSize attribute to verify the size of the file. Large files can be slow to retrieve.
member.param:
The url for the file. This parameter must match the TextFileUrl value returned by the SearchFilings, GetLastFilings, and GetRecentFilings operations. You can omit the case-sensitive http://www.sec.gov/ Archives/edgar/data/ prefix. Examples: 789019/000103221002000454/000
1032210-02-000454.txt
Indicate whether the system should attempt to tag a text file as HTML for more elegant consumption by a browser.. Examples: true

member.summary: Returns LIBOR interest rates for a specific type, currency and date, including today.Note: Due to the BBA's discontinuation of LIBOR fixing for a number of currencies and maturities, only the following currencies are supported for the remaining maturities of Overnight, OneWeek, OneMonth, TwoMonths, ThreeMonths, SixMonths and OneYear:USDEURGBPCHFJPY
member.param:
The type of LIBOR rate.
Only the following maturities are supported:
Overnight
OneWeek
OneMonth
TwoMonths
ThreeMonths
SixMonths
OneYear Examples: OneWeek

The currency for the LIBOR rate.
Only the following currencies are supported:
USD
EUR
GBP
CHF
JPY Examples: USD
The date for the rate. This can be any date for which the rate is available (typically back to 1998). Examples: 8/24/2014

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteLogos.GetLogo(System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteLogos.IdentifierTypes)
member.summary: Get the logo for a company.
member.param: The identifier for the company as determined by the IdentifierType parameter. Examples: MSFT

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the SEC Central Index Key for the company.
Use the LookupCIK operation to find the CIK for a company.
CUSIP: Identifier is the CUSIP for the company.
CUSIPS are unique security identifiers managed by The CUSIP Service Bureau.
Symbol: Identifier is the symbol for the company, e.g. DELL.
Supports multiple Symbologies, check here for details.
ISIN: Identifier is the ISIN 12-character alpha numeric code identifying a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a Swiss financial instrument. Examples: Symbol

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteNASDAQLastSale.GetBar(System.String,System.String,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteNASDAQLastSale.TickPrecisions,System.Int32)
member.summary: Returns a single summarized quote bar for a specific time during the trading day.
member.param: The symbol for the security. Examples: MSFT
The ending time for the summarized trade bar. The time may be entered in 12-hr or 24-hr format: HH:MM AM/PM or HH:MM Examples: 10:00 AM

The precision unit to apply to the summarized quote bars. Choose:
Seconds to summarize quotes by the number of seconds specified by Periods.
Minutes to summarize quotes by the number of minutes specified by Periods.
Hours to summarize quotes by the number of hours specified by Periods.
For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=15 will return one quote bar every fifteen minutes, including the open, high, low and close within that fifteen minute period. Examples: Minutes

Used in combination with Precision to define the number of units to apply to summarized quote bars. For instance, Precision=Minutes and Period=15 will return one summarized quote bar every fifteen minutes. Examples: 15

summary.p: The precision unit to apply to the ticks of the chart. Choose:

ul.li: Tick to draw one point per trade (could be thousands for highly traded securities). TickPeriods does not apply in this case.
Milliseconds to summarize trades by the number of milliseconds specified by TickPeriods.
Second to summarize trades by the number of seconds specified by TickPeriods.
Minute to summarize trades by the number of minutes specified by TickPeriods.

summary.p: For instance TickPeriod=2 and TickPrecision=Minute will plot one value of the chart for trades executed every two minutes.

member.name: P:Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteRates.ChartDesign.TickPeriods
member.summary: Used in combination with TickPrecision to define the number of points displayed on the chart. For instance TickPeriods=5 with TickPrecision=Minute will display one data point every 5 minutes with the point being the average price for that period.

If a daily value is available, then the last daily value is returned. member.param: The type of rate. Use GetRateDescription to learn more about supported rates. Examples: InterestRateSwapSpread10Year

member.name: M:Xignite.Sdk.Api.XigniteRates.GetAverageRate(Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteRates.RateTypes,Xignite.Sdk.Api.Models.XigniteRates.PeriodTypes,System.String)
member.summary: Returns an average interest rate for a specific date and period.Average rates are available for H15 rates for weekly, monthly and annual average periods.Average interest rates are calculated by averaging all the interest rates published over that period. The AsOfDate parameter depends on the PeriodType chosen: For Monthly rates, the average rate is the average of all the rates from the first to the last of the month. AsOfDate must be the first day of the month. For Weekly rates, the average rate is the average of all the rates from the first to the last day of the week. AsOfDate must be the last day of the week. For Yearly rates, the average rate is the average of all the rates from the first to the last day of the year. AsOfDate must be the first day of the year. Any InterBank rate requested through this operation requires a XigniteInterBanks subscription.
member.param: The type of rate. Use GetRateDescription to learn more about supported rates. Examples: FederalFunds
The type of period (Weekly, Monthly, Annually). Daily will return the same value as GetRate(). Examples: Monthly
The date for the rate. This can be any date for which the rate is available. Use GetRateStatistics to find available dates. Examples: 6/1/2012

The identifier type. Valid values are:
CIK: Identifier is the SEC Central Index Key for the company.

Symbol: Identifier is the symbol for the company, e.g. MSFT, DELL, or ORCL.
Supports multiple Symbologies, check here for details.
ISIN: Identifier is the ISIN 12-character alpha numeric code identifying a security.
Valoren: Identifier is the Valoren number assigned to a Swiss financial instrument. Examples: Symbol
Only releases published after this date will be listed. Examples: 12/7/2006
